{
  "card_id": "continuation_order_block",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Continuation Order Block",
  "aliases": [
    "continuation ob",
    "Continuation OB",
    "Trend Continuation Order Block",
    "trend continuation order block"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "An order block formed after a confirmed change in state of delivery or reversal sequence, during a retracement. Price sweeps a short-term swing high/low into a point of interest (fair value gap, prior order block, or liquidity) and closes through a series of opposing candles, validating the block. It provides a continuation entry aligned with higher timeframe bias, with stops at the new protected swing.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Establish a higher timeframe bias confirmed by a change in state of delivery or prior reversal sequence.",
    "Identify a retracement where price sweeps a short-term swing high (bearish) or low (bullish) into a point of interest (fair value gap, prior order block, or liquidity).",
    "The retracement should consist of a series of opposing-close candles (down-close for bullish, up-close for bearish) that reach the point of interest.",
    "Price must close through the series (above the bodies for bullish, below for bearish) to validate the order block.",
    "The order block is the range of the last opposing candle(s); the new swing high/low formed by the sweep acts as the protected level.",
    "Confirmation includes displacement (aggressive move with fair value gaps) in the bias direction, supported by multi-timeframe alignment and small wicks on higher timeframe candles.",
    "Without a defined point of interest, an opposing candle is only valid if accompanied by SMT divergence on a correlated asset.",
    "In a trending market, locate the last candlestick before a sharp impulsive move in the trend direction; mark it as a demand order block in an uptrend or supply order block in a downtrend.",
    "Ensure no change of character (CHoCH) against the prevailing trend has occurred prior to the order block formation.",
    "Confirm the order block is part of a sequence of trending impulses, not at a reversal point."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "The Continuation Order Block offers a high-probability entry for trend continuation, especially after missing the initial reversal. Enter on the close-through or retest of the block; place stops at the new protected swing to enhance risk-to-reward. For large blocks, use the 50% mean threshold. Target higher timeframe liquidity or gaps with minimum 2R. Multiple continuation blocks may form, allowing re-entries while bias and multi-timeframe alignment persist.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering before the continuation order block is fully validated (e.g., before close through opposing series or without prior change in state of delivery).",
    "Accepting a candle as a valid order block when it did not reach into a point of interest (e.g., no fair value gap, prior order block, or liquidity sweep).",
    "Placing the stop at the original reversal extreme or order block low instead of the new protected swing created by the sweep.",
    "Taking entries at the full opening price of a large order block instead of using the mean threshold (50% of range) for better risk-to-reward.",
    "Chasing price after aggressive displacement without waiting for a retest of the order block.",
    "Trading without multi-timeframe alignment, or confusing a retracement with a reversal, leading to entries against the higher timeframe bias.",
    "Mistaking a slow, non-displaced move (no V-shaped reversal/fair value gaps) for a valid continuation setup.",
    "Mistaking a continuation order block for a reversal order block, which forms after a change of character.",
    "Assuming all order blocks in a trend are continuation without checking for underlying CHoCH."
  ],
